awards: [{'title': 'Germline biomarkers of melanoma immunotherapy: an international consortium', 'description': 'This grant ($898,263 U.S. Dollars) is awarded for the formation of the first large international consortium (IO GEM) to explore germline genetic factors as modulators of MM ICI response, toxicity and survival. IO GEM pools >9,800 MM patients treated by anti-CTLA4 and anti-PD1 ICI, to perform a first large genome-wide association study (GWAS) to identify and validate germline genetic factors as biomarkers and actionable clinical targets modulating MM ICI efficacy and survival (Specific Aim 1) and MM ICI toxicity (Specific Aim 2). The GWAS loci will be tested for target potential by innovative platforms investigating their role in immune and peripheral T-cell component. Supported by the strong preliminary data, we propose that unlike prior GWAS disease risk designs, the putative germline predictors of ICI outcomes will exert substantial clinically actionable effects. We also suggest that besides biomarker discovery, the proposed design may likely point to novel pathways that could eventually be targeted in more efficient, yet less toxic MM ICI therapy. \n\n', 'issuer': 'Melanoma Research Alliance: Team Science Award ', 'date': {'month': None, 'day': None, 'year': 2020}}, {'title': 'AI&II Postdoc stipend 2018', 'description': 'This grant (â‚¬70,000) is given to postdoctoral talent to continue their research at a crucial stage in their career towards successful future grant applications.
